{{For|the living American political activist|Alice Green}} __NOTOC__ {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} {{Infobox person |name = Alice Stopford Green |image = Alicestopfordgreen.jpg |imagesize = 180px |caption = Portrait taken in the 1880s |birth_date = {{Birth date|1847|5|30|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Kells, County Meath]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|1929|05|28|1847|05|30|df=y}} |death_place = [[Dublin]], Ireland |spouse = {{marriage|[[John Richard Green]]|1877|1883|end=died}} |party = |occupation = Historian, political activist and public representative |signature = }} '''Alice Stopford Green''' (30 May 1847 – 28 May 1929) was an Irish [[historian]] and [[Irish nationalism|nationalist]].
She was born Alice Sophia Amelia Stopford in [[Kells, County Meath|Kells]], [[County Meath]]. Her father Edward Adderley Stopford was Rector of Kells and [[Archdeacon of Meath]]. Her paternal grandfather was [[Edward Stopford (bishop)|Edward Stopford]], the [[Church of Ireland]] [[Diocese of Meath|Bishop of Meath]],<ref name="rjtechne1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.iol.ie/~rjtechne/century130703/1900s/asgmcd.htm |title=Alice Stopford Green's Life |publisher=Iol.ie |date= |accessdate=5 February 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090107014922/http://www.iol.ie/~rjtechne/century130703/1900s/asgmcd.htm| archivedate= 7 January 2009 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> and she was a cousin of [[Stopford Brooke (chaplain)|Stopford Brooke]] and [[Mother Mary Clare]]. From 1874 to 1877 she lived in London where she met the historian [[John Richard Green]].<ref name="britannica1">{{Cite web| url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/244863/Alice-Stopford-Green |title=Alice Stopford Green |publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica |date=28 May 1929 |accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref> They were married in Chester on 14 June 1877.<ref>"England, Cheshire Parish Registers, 1538-2000", index, FamilySearch (https://familysearch.org/pal:/MM9.1.1/F7M6-SFR : accessed 11 Mar 2014), John Richard Green and Alice Sophia Amelia Stopford, 1877.</ref> He died in 1883. [[John Morley, 1st Viscount Morley of Blackburn|John Morley]] published her first historical work ''Henry II'' in 1888.
In the 1890s she became interested in Irish history and the nationalist movement as a result of her friendship with John Francis Taylor.<ref name="rjtechne1"/> She was vocal in her opposition to English colonial policy in South Africa during the [[Boer Wars]] and supported [[Roger Casement]]'s Congo Reform movement.<ref name="rjtechne1"/> Her 1908 book ''The Making of Ireland and its Undoing'' argued for the sophistication and richness of the native Irish civilisation.<ref name="britannica1"/> Stopford Green was active in efforts to make the prospect of [[Irish Home Rule bills|Home Rule]] more palatable to [[Ulster Unionists#1880s to 1921|Ulster Unionists]].<ref name="rjtechne1"/> She was closely involved in the [[Howth gun-running]].
She moved to Dublin in 1918 where her house at 90 [[St Stephen's Green]] became an intellectual centre.<ref name="rjtechne1"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ricorso.net/rx/az-data/index.htm|title=Alice Stopford Green |publisher=Ricorso|date= |accessdate=5 February 2009}}</ref> She supported the pro-[[Anglo-Irish Treaty|Treaty]] side in the [[Irish Civil War]] and was among the first nominees to the newly formed [[Seanad Éireann (Irish Free State)|Seanad Éireann]] in 1922, where she served as an independent member until her death in 1929.<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=http://oireachtas.ie/members-hist/default.asp?housetype=1&HouseNum=1922&MemberID=1345&ConstID=215|title=Mrs. Alice Stopford Green|work=Oireachtas Members Database|accessdate=1 July 2009}}</ref>
==Works== *''Henry the Second'' (1903) first pub. 1888. *''Town Life in the Fifteenth Century Vol. I'' (1894) *''Town Life in the Fifteenth Century Vol. II'' (1894) *''The making of Ireland and its undoing, 1200-1600'' (1909) first pub. 1908. *''Irish nationality'' (c1911). *''The old Irish world'' (1912) *''Loyalty and disloyalty: what it means in Ireland'' ([1918?]) *''A History of the Irish State to 1014'' published in 1925, was her last major work.
==Further reading== *R. B. McDowell, ''Alice Stopford-Green: A Passionate Historian'' (1967). *Léon Ó Bróin, ''Protestant Nationalists in Revolutionary Ireland, The Stopford Connection'' (1985).
