{{About|the magazine ''Ancient Warfare''|warfare in Antiquity|Ancient warfare}} [[File:Ancient warfare cover.jpg|thumb|Cover of an issue of ''Ancient Warfare'' (art by [[J. Shumate]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://community.imaginefx.com/fxpose/johnny_shumates_portfolio/default.aspx |title=Photos: Johnny Shumate's Portfolio |publisher=Imaginefx |accessdate=1 October 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004213608/http://community.imaginefx.com/fxpose/johnny_shumates_portfolio/default.aspx |archivedate=4 October 2013 }}</ref>]] '''''Ancient Warfare''''' is a glossy Dutch bi-monthly [[military history]] magazine.
==Profile== ''Ancient Warfare'' was started in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Caroline Wazer|title=The New 'Ancient History' Magazine May Be Idealistic, But We're Glad it Exists|url=http://historybuff.com/the-new-ancient-history-magazine-may-be-idealistic-but-were-glad-it-exists-ZrYRD60Kdmp9|accessdate=2 January 2017|work=HistoryBuff|date=11 December 2015}}</ref> It is published by the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] publishing company Karwansaray.<ref name=kpub>{{cite web|title=About Ancient Warfare|url=http://www.karwansaraypublishers.com/pw/ancient-warfare/about/|publisher=Karwansaray Publishers|accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref> The magazine was founded by [[Jasper Oorthuys]], who now serves as managing director and editor-in-chief. The current editor is archaeologist [[Josho Brouwers]].<ref name=kpub/>
Most of the magazine's feature articles focus on a central theme per issue.<ref>{{cite news|author=William Brown|title=Ancient Warfare Magazine|url=http://www.ancient.eu/review/94/|accessdate=30 December 2015|work=Ancient History Encyclopedia|date=28 October 2015}}</ref> These include articles on a specific [[general]], campaign or more abstract phenomenon such as [[siege]]s. Each issue usually starts off with a historical introduction to the theme. The introduction is usually followed by an article that delves into relevant sources for the theme, such as a historical narrative or an [[archaeology|archaeological]] source. The theme is then fleshed out by articles on warriors, battles and generals that fit that issue's theme. Among the authors are well-known specialists like Bob Bennett, [[Duncan Campbell (ancient historian)|Duncan B. Campbell]], [[Ross Cowan]], [[Lukas de Blois]], [[Stephen English]], [[Adrian Murdoch]], Joseph Pietrykowski, [[Jona Lendering]], and Mike Roberts.
The magazine also includes news and letters from readers, as well as reviews of relevant books, games, models, and [[museum]]s. The illustrations include original artwork, maps and photographs of artifacts. Online free features of the magazine include the editor's [[blog]] and a [[podcast]] which is published to coincide with the magazine themes.
Other spin-offs were specials on the [[Battle of the Teutoburg Forest]] and the nature of the Roman ''[[centuria]]''. Since 2012, the yearly special is published in the form of a hardcover book. The first was ''Edge of Empire'' (2012), a reworked English translation of an originally Dutch book by [[Jona Lendering]] and Arjan Bosman on the Roman occupation of the Low Countries. The second was ''Henchmen of Ares: Warriors and Warfare in Early Greece'' (2013) written by editor Josho Brouwers and based on his PhD dissertation on Early Greek warfare.
The magazine is registered as {{ISSN|1874-7019}}.
