'''Edward Mann Butler''' (July 13, 1784 &ndash; November 1, 1855) was one of [[Kentucky]]'s most prominent early educators. He is best remembered as being the first president of what would become the [[University of Louisville]] and heading the first [[Public school (government funded)|public school]] in Kentucky.
Butler was born in [[Baltimore, Maryland|Baltimore]]. After graduating from [[St. Mary's College of Maryland|St Mary's College]], Butler practiced law and served as a school teacher in various locations, including [[Maysville, Kentucky|Maysville]], [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]], [[Versailles, Kentucky|Versailles]] and [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]]. He was the president of the Jefferson Seminary (which later became the University of Louisville) from 1813 to 1816. In 1822 he became the head of the grammar department at Lexington's [[Transylvania University]], and then returned to head the Jefferson Seminary in 1829.
He is also considered Kentucky's first reliable [[historian]], with his first complete work being released in 1834. At the time of his death, he was working on a detailed history of the [[Ohio River]] Valley. He was killed on November 1, 1855 in a [[St Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]] train wreck.
