'''Sir Kenneth Clinton Wheare''', [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]] (26 March 1907 – 7 September 1979)<ref name="ADB">{{cite web | url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/wheare-sir-kenneth-clinton-12005 | title=Wheare, Sir Kenneth Clinton (1907–1979) | work=[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]] | publisher=[[Australian National University]] | accessdate=14 July 2011 | author=Poynter, J. R.}}</ref> was an Australian academic, who spent most of his career at [[Oxford University]] in England.<ref>[http://www.oxforddnb.com/index/101031822/ Biography], ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', 2004.</ref>  He was an expert on the constitutions of the [[British Commonwealth]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Markwell |first=Donald |authorlink=Donald Markwell |title=Constitutional Conventions and the Headship of State: Australian Experience |publisher=Connor Court|year=2016 |isbn=9781925501155 }} Appendix 3: Two Constitutional Scholars: Sir Kenneth Wheare and Dr [[Eugene Forsey]].</ref>

==Early life and family==
Wheare was educated at [[Scotch College, Melbourne]]<ref name="ADB" /> and was later a student at [[Oriel College, Oxford]], gaining a [[first class degree]] in [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]] and also undertaking postgraduate study. He met his wife Joan (1915-2013) when he was her tutor.<ref>{{cite news|title=Joan Wheare: Rebel with many causes|url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/community/obituaries/obits/10789899.Rebel_with_many_causes_who__was_Oxford___s____urban_guerilla___/|accessdate=22 March 2015|publisher=Oxford Mail|date=7 November 2013}}</ref> One of their sons is [[Tom Wheare]].

==Career==

===Political career===
Wheare served on the [[Oxford City Council]] from 1940 to 1957.

===Academic career===
In 1944, he was appointed [[Gladstone Professor of Government]] at [[All Souls College, Oxford|All Souls College]]. In 1956, he became [[Rector (college)|Rector]] of [[Exeter College, Oxford]]. A gargoyle of his likeness is carved on the Bodleian Library, visible from the Exeter College Fellow's Garden.<ref name="ADB" />

Wheare was Chairman of the [[Rhodes Trust]] (1962–69), President of the [[British Academy]] (1967–71), Chancellor of the [[University of Liverpool]] from 1972. He was also a [[Vice-Chancellor of the University of Oxford]] from 1964–66.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.admin.ox.ac.uk/vc/position/previousvice-chancellors/|title=Previous Vice-Chancellors | publisher=[[University of Oxford]], UK|accessdate=14 July 2011}}</ref>

==Honours==
He was appointed [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George]] (CMG) in 1953 and was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1966.

In 2017, [[Oxford Brookes University]] named a newly rebuilt lecture hall after Wheare.

