[[File:Birgit_Ridderstedt_Centenary_group_2014_(4)_(cropped).JPG|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Birgit_Ridderstedt_Centenary_group_2014_(4)_(cropped).JPG|alt=The woman on the left is wearing a "Squaw Dress."|thumb|The woman on the left is wearing a "squaw dress."]]
A '''squaw''', '''fiesta''', '''Kachina''', '''Tohono''' or '''patio''' dress{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=375}} is an [[Fashion in the United States|American style of dress]] developed in [[Arizona]]<nowiki/>. It became popular during the 1940s and 50s, and many famous women owned these dresses. It was developed primarily by [[Dolores Gonzales]] and [[Cele Peterson]], who [[Cultural appropriation|appropriated]] the look from [[Native American fashion]]. The word "[[squaw]]", once used for [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American women]] and thus for this fashion, is now seen as offensive and the other names for the dress, such as "fiesta" or "patio", are preferred.
== About == The squaw dress could be either one or two pieces, with a two piece "dress" consisting of a skirt and a blouse.<ref name=":02">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16630328/press_and_sunbulletin/|title=The Squaw Dress from the Southwest|last=Dugas|first=Gaile|date=1955-05-18|work=Press and Sun-Bulletin|access-date=2018-01-17|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=45|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> They were made with [[cotton]] or [[Chintz|calico print]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16657811/daily_world/|title='Squaw' Dress Goes East as American Indians Give New Inspiration to Designers|last=|first=|date=1952-04-02|work=Daily World|access-date=2018-01-18|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=18|via=Newpapers.com}}</ref> The skirt part of the dress is [[Pleat|pleated]], [[Gather (sewing)|gathered]] or fully gathered with three-tiers.<ref name=":02" />{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=375}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16658037/star_tribune/|title=Arizona Styles are Informal|last=Reynolds|first=Aileen|date=1952-11-30|work=Star Tribune|access-date=2018-01-18|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=68|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The dresses were often colorful and incorporated [[rickrack]] as well.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tucson.com/lifestyles/modernism-week-squaw-dress-trend-kick-started-in-tucson/article_728bbbc7-82b7-55d0-9c95-3553ef3485c7.html|title=Modernism Week: "Squaw" dress trend kick-started in Tucson|last=Cook|first=Kristen|date=26 September 2015|work=Arizona Daily Star|access-date=2018-01-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928003419/http://tucson.com/lifestyles/modernism-week-squaw-dress-trend-kick-started-in-tucson/article_728bbbc7-82b7-55d0-9c95-3553ef3485c7.html|archive-date=28 September 2015|dead-url=|language=en}}</ref> The hemlines sometimes copied [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] basket designs.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=6 July 1953|title=Squaw Skirts: Southwest Resort Vacationers Bring Back an Old Tribal Style|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DEgEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA35&dq=life%20magazine%20lloyd%20kiva%20new&pg=PA34#v=onepage&q&f=true|journal=Life|volume=35|issue=1|pages=34-35|via=}}</ref> Many squaw dresses would be accessorized with ''concho'' belts, squash blossom necklaces and [[turquoise]] earrings.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=383}}{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=387}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16657425/arizona_daily_star/|title=Fall Styles for Tucson|last=|first=|date=1949-11-06|work=Arizona Daily Star|access-date=2018-01-18|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=25|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Later versions of the squaw dress included metallic fabrics and [[glitter]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16658733/la_grande_observer/|title=Native Fashion Takes on Glitter|last=|first=|date=1955-05-27|work=La Grande Observer|access-date=2018-01-19|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=3|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16658841/the_terre_haute_tribune/|title=Squaw Dress is Tops|last=|first=|date=1958-07-27|work=The Terre Haute Tribune|access-date=2018-01-19|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=19|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>
The garment was described as being comfortable and flattering to most figures, according to ''[[The Arizona Republic]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16630497/arizona_republic/|title=To Sew a Pretty Seam for a Pretty Squaw|last=|first=|date=1958|work=Arizona Republic|access-date=2018-01-17|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=140|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The dresses were lightweight and comfortable to wear on hot days.<ref name=":1" /> They did not require [[ironing]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16657917/the_decatur_daily_review/|title='Squaw Dress' is Favorite for Casual Wear|last=|first=|date=1952-04-09|work=The Decatur Daily Review|access-date=2018-01-18|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=18|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In addition, the dress could be worn for many different kinds of occasions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16658489/tucson_daily_citizen/|title=Squaw Dress Forms Basis of Industry|last=|first=|date=1954-02-19|work=Tucson Daily Citizen|access-date=2018-01-19|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=72|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> == History == [[File:Western_fashions_in_Arizona.ogg|thumb|PSA about Western fashions in Arizona, including the "squaw dress."]] The original designs that served as the basis of the squaw dress skirt were found in [[Navajo]] broomstick skirts.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=384}} These skirts and blouses that the Navajo wore were, in turn, based on [[1870s in Western fashion|1870s and 1880s European fashions]] and fabrics.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=384}}<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16658397/press_and_sunbulletin/|title=Squaw Dresses|last=|first=|date=1954|work=Press and Sun-Bulletin|access-date=2018-01-19|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=14|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> By 1910, a unique style had developed which incorporated Navajo ideals of beauty and it become widespread among Navajo women.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=385}} The dresses also reflected a sense of "cultural revitalization, high self-esteem, and ethnic identity," according to professor of [[Native American studies|American Indian studies]] Nancy Parezo and Angelina R. Jones.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=385}}<ref name=":1" /> [[Bodice|Bodices]] and [[Blouse|blouses]] worn with the skirts reflected different origins.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=385}} Loose blouses paired with the skirt came from [[Western Apache people|Western Apache]] and [[Tohono O'odham]] dress.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=385}} The squaw dress also had Mexican influences.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=387}}
The different looks of the dress were based on different types of popular [[Navajo]], [[Mexicans|Mexican]], [[Tohono O'odham]] and [[Western Apache people|Western Apache]] dresses.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=375}} [[Zuni]] and [[Hopi]] dress were also an inspiration.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16658596/great_falls_tribune/|title=Squaw Dress Comes in New Sophisticated Variations|last=|first=|date=1955-03-24|work=Great Falls Tribune|access-date=2018-01-19|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=18|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The squaw dress also shows influence from the [[New Look (style of clothing)|New Look]] in fashion.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=383}} Using the term "[[squaw]]" to name the dresses evoked a connection to Native American culture.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=388}} In addition, the Native American roots of the design made the dresses seem like uniquely "American" clothing items.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=375}} The dress also became synonymous with the [[Southwestern United States|Southwest]].<ref name=":1" />
The squaw dress started out as a trend in the [[American Southwest]] in the 1940s and went nationwide in the 1950s.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=374-375}} The first designers of the squaw dress are unknown, however designers such as [[Dolores Gonzales]] and [[Cele Peterson]] were selling dresses they called "squaw Dresses" by 1948.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=388}} Bill and Elizabeth Macey who owned a clothing [[Factory|manufacturing plant]] called the Arizona Shirt Company, created a design for the squaw dress as well.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16630594/tucson_daily_citizen/|title=Style Trade Route Now Originates In Tucson|last=Keating|first=Micheline|date=1952-02-09|work=Tucson Daily Citizen|access-date=2018-01-17|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=6|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> The Maceys' design was considered "smart," but authentic, according to ''[[The Arizona Republic]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16658113/arizona_republic/|title=Shirt Concern Popularized Squaw Dress|last=|first=|date=1953-02-15|work=Arizona Republic|access-date=2018-01-19|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=88|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> George Fine who owned Georgie of Arizona was another major creator of the dresses.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://arizonasonoranewsservice.com/the-squaw-dress-tucsons-controversial-but-unique-fashion-history/|title=The squaw dress: Tucson’s controversial but unique fashion history|last=Driver|first=Maggie|date=21 April 2016|website=Arizona Sonora News|language=en-US|archive-url=http://arizonasonoranewsservice.com/the-squaw-dress-tucsons-controversial-but-unique-fashion-history/|archive-date=8 January 2017|dead-url=|access-date=2018-01-17}}</ref> [[Lloyd Kiva New]], a [[Cherokee]] designer, also created squaw dresses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1356&dat=19551102&id=CgEkAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vAQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4318,423474&hl=en|title=Cherokee Designer Tops In Squaw Fashions|last=Roe|first=Dorothy|date=2 November 1955|work=Ocala Star-Banner|access-date=18 January 2018|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=}}</ref> Eventually [[J. C. Penney|J.C. Penney]], [[F. W. Woolworth Company|Woolworth's]] and [[Neiman Marcus]] were selling versions of the squaw dress.<ref name=":1" /> In 1954, [[Gimbels|Gimble's]] department store in [[Philadelphia]] held a [[fashion show]] where "Princess Red Rock" modeled the dress on the runway and the store sold versions of the dress.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WslF1f7Y6wgC&lpg=PA259&dq=%22squaw%20dress%22&pg=PA259#v=onepage&q=%22squaw%20dress%22&f=false|title=Unpacking Culture: Art and Commodity in Colonial and Postcolonial Worlds|last=Phillips|first=Ruth B.|last2=Steiner|first2=Christopher B.|date=1999-01-30|publisher=University of California Press|year=|isbn=9780520207974|location=|pages=259|language=en}}</ref> Women such as [[Mamie Eisenhower]], [[Pat Nixon]], [[Cyd Charisse]] and [[Elsa Martinelli]] were seen in these dresses.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/10/movies/elsa-martinelli-italian-model-and-actress-dies-at-82.html|title=Elsa Martinelli, Italian Model and Actress, Dies at 82|last=Sandomir|first=Richard|date=2017-07-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2018-01-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>
Squaw dresses went out of fashion nationally by 1960, but remained popular in the [[Southwestern United States|Southwest United States]] and also in [[Square dance|square dancing]] and [[Rodeo|rodeos]].{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=392}} When the style was revisited in later decades, the dresses were labeled as "Western wear" and given new names.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=393}}{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=395-396}} These dresses are today more often called patio or fiesta dresses.<ref name=":1" />
== Tucson Based Dress Designers (1950-1960) == * Dolores Resort Wear * Alpha Sportswear or Alpha of Tucson * Cele Peterson * Costa Co. * Danzy Manufacturing Co. * Faye Creations and Western Fun Togs (Frye R. Cohen) * Georgie of Arizona (George Fine) * Imlach of Tucson (James Imlach) * Desert Togs (Bea Barcelo) * GRETA’S (Greta De Luca)
== Controversy == Because the squaw dress [[Cultural appropriation|appropriates]] from various different Indigenous people's clothing and because of the use of the word "[[squaw]]," there were people who were uncomfortable with the fashion.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=390-391}} Designer [[Dolores Gonzales]] admitted that she had taken the idea for the design from Native American women's clothing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16626885/arizona_daily_star/|title='Dior of the Desert'|last=Henry|first=Bonnie|date=1995-02-23|work=Arizona Daily Star|access-date=2018-01-17|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=29|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In a 1954 article in ''[[Arizona Daily Star|The Arizona Daily Star]]'', the dresses were described as "What was once worn proudly by Indian squaws is now being worn across the country by many women."<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/16626059/arizona_daily_star/|title=Even Ike's Mamie Wears Squaw Dresses From Dolores' Shop|last=Roth|first=Bernie|date=1954-10-17|work=Arizona Daily Star|access-date=2018-01-17|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|pages=20|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> [[Anthropologist]] Adelaide Law believed that the dresses were blatant ploys to cash in on "tourist trade."{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=391}} Curator [[Frederic Huntington Douglas|Frederick H. Douglas]], who was known for his early exhibits of [[Native American fashion]], felt that using the name "squaw" was disrespectful.{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=391}} Around the same time the dresses went out of fashion in the 1960s, the Native American community began to decry the use of the word "squaw," which was seen as [[Pejorative|derogatory]].{{Sfn|Parezo|Jones|2009|p=393}} Modern use of the word "squaw" to describe the dress is seen as culturally insensitive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.beyondbuckskin.com/2012/03/native-fashion-and-squaw-dress.html|title=Native Fashion and the Squaw Dress|last=Metcalfe|first=Jessica R.|date=24 March 2012|website=Beyond Buckskin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170716141017/http://www.beyondbuckskin.com/2012/03/native-fashion-and-squaw-dress.html|archive-date=16 July 2017|dead-url=|access-date=2018-01-18}}</ref>
